x4freetext: Natural carbon target was used for 12C.
The magnetic field of the spectrometer
was measured by a null reading magnetometer. A
scintillation counter placed at the "image" position
of the magnetic spectrometer was used to count the
scattered protons. It consisted of a 931-A
photomultiplier tube and a scintillating screen
prepared by dusting zinc sulfide powder on the end of
Both 12C and 13C targets were used in the experiment.
Since the 12C and 13C scattered protons could not be
separated at the small scattering angles the number
of counts had to be corrected for the 12C present.
Both a normal carbon target and 13C enriched target
were placed on the target backing. The target backing
could be raised or lowered so that the two foils
could be alternately placed in the proton beam.
Each point of the yield curves for
E=1.65 N1 minus 0.65 N2, where E is the number of
protons that would be scattered from a pure 13C
target, N1 is the number of protons scattered from
